Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Chop the @new potatoes{2} into quarters, finely
chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped, stalks discarded), pull the
@oregano{1}(leaves pulled off stalks) leaves off their stalks and roughly chop
them too. Put your potatoes on a #baking tray{}, drizzle over enough oil until
your potatoes are coated, add a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and put in your oven
to roast for ~{25-30%mins}, until crispy.

In the meantime, coat the @pork fillet{1} with the @Dijon mustard{3}, using
either a #pastry brush{} or the back of a #spoon{} until fully coated.

> Make sure you leave a bit of mustard to serve with your pork at the end.

Mix together the @panko breadcrumbs{4}, parsley, half your oregano, a good
glug of oil, a pinch of salt and a really good grind of @black pepper{grind}.
Tip this breadcrumb mixture onto your #chopping board{} and roll your mustardy
pork fillet gently in it, until evenly coated.

> Remember to wash your hands after handling raw meat!

Place your pork on a lightly oiled baking tray and pop in your oven to cook
for ~{20-25%mins}, then remove from your oven and allow to rest for
~{5%mins}.

> The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While your pork and potatoes are cooking, tackle the broccoli. Chop the
@Tenderstem® broccoli{1}(stems chopped in half lengthways) stems in half
lengthways.

About ~{5%mins} before your pork and potatoes are ready, add a drizzle of
oil to a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Add your broccoli to the pan along
with your remaining oregano, sprinkle over a pinch of salt and a good grind of
pepper and throw in a splash of @water{1%tbsp per person}. Put the #lid{} on
and cook for ~{3-4%mins}, then remove from the heat.

Cut your pork into slices about 1cm thick and serve with your potatoes,
broccoli and a small dollop of mustard if you have any left. Enjoy!